{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535434"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:55:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:55:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15443"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15443","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15443"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.69,0.03,0.02,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8134"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113392"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8134"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15443"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95413"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2145"},{"type":"tags","id":"2360"},{"type":"tags","id":"3652"},{"type":"tags","id":"4701"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19717"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30610"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44425"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46762"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113392"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department after sustaining a needlestick injury 30 minutes ago. She is a junior doctor who was attempting to recap a needle after taking blood from a patient known to be HIV-positive. The needle penetrated through her glove and caused a deep puncture wound to her right index finger which bled freely. The source patient has been on antiretroviral therapy for five years but their viral load status is unknown. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears anxious but well. Her vital signs are within normal limits. There is a small puncture wound on her right index finger with no active bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Single-drug post-exposure prophylaxis","Three-drug post-exposure prophylaxis","Immediate HIV testing only","Delayed post-exposure prophylaxis in 24 hours","Reassurance and observation only"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario describes a significant occupational exposure to HIV through a deep needlestick injury from a known HIV-positive source patient. According to the Australian National Guidelines for Post-Exposure Prophylaxis after Non-Occupational and Occupational Exposure to HIV, PEP is typically recommended for percutaneous injuries from HIV-positive sources. However, current evidence suggests that HIV transmission does not occur from source patients with undetectable viral loads. In cases where the source has a recent undetectable viral load, the decision to commence PEP involves shared decision-making between the healthcare provider and exposed person, weighing the minimal risks of PEP against the extremely low transmission risk. When viral load information is not immediately available, as in this case, PEP initiation should not be delayed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThree-drug post-exposure prophylaxis\u003C/strong\u003E is the current recommended approach for significant occupational exposures to HIV. The standard regimen combines two nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitors (Truvada\u2122 - co-formulated tenofovir DF 300mg + emtricitabine 200mg once daily) with an integrase inhibitor (either raltegravir 400mg twice daily or dolutegravir 50mg once daily), continued for 28 days. Treatment should be started as soon as possible after exposure, ideally within 2 hours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESingle-drug post-exposure prophylaxis\u003C/strong\u003E is inadequate for preventing HIV transmission and is not recommended in any circumstance. This approach would provide suboptimal protection and could potentially lead to drug resistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance and observation only\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate given the significant nature of the exposure. While the risk of transmission is low (approximately 0.3% from a needlestick injury), the consequences of HIV infection are serious enough to warrant prophylaxis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate HIV testing only\u003C/strong\u003E would be insufficient. While baseline testing should be performed, it only establishes the healthcare worker\u0027s HIV status at the time of exposure and does not prevent HIV transmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelayed post-exposure prophylaxis\u003C/strong\u003E would reduce the effectiveness of prevention. PEP should be initiated as soon as possible after exposure, ideally within 2 hours, and definitely within 72 hours. Delaying treatment by 24 hours would reduce its efficacy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditional management should include counselling about potential side effects of PEP, the importance of adherence, and the need for follow-up HIV testing at appropriate intervals. The incident should also prompt a review of safe sharps handling practices, particularly the hazards of recapping needles.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["HIV post-exposure prophylaxis should be initiated within 72 hours of exposure, ideally within 2 hours.","The risk of HIV transmission from a needlestick injury with HIV-positive blood is approximately 0.3%.","Three-drug post-exposure prophylaxis regimens combining two nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitors with an integrase inhibitor are recommended for significant occupational exposures to HIV."],"references":["PEP Guidelines. Available at: https://pep.guidelines.org.au/","PEP Quick Guide for Occupational Exposures | National Clinician Consultation Center [Internet]. Available at: https://nccc.ucsf.edu/clinical-resources/pep-resources/pep-quick-guide-for-occupational-exposures/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95413"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15443"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95413"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-11T21:11:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-11T21:13:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8134"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113392"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/a